-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find the unique residue n with 0 ≤ n < 1399 such that 160 n ≡ 1 (mod 1399). 2. [Key Idea] Because 1400 = 35·40 and 1400 ≡ 1 (mod 1399), 40 has inverse 35; writing 160 = 4·40 lets us obtain the inverse of 160 by multiplying the inverses of 40 and 4. 3. [Proof] Method 1 (modular manipulations). • Since 1400 = 35·40 and 1400 ≡ 1 (mod 1399), 40⁻¹ ≡ 35 (mod 1399). • Likewise, 4·350 = 1400 ≡ 1 (mod 1399), hence 4⁻¹ ≡ 350 (mod 1399). • Because 160 = 4·40, 160⁻¹ ≡ (4·40)⁻¹ ≡ 4⁻¹ · 40⁻¹ ≡ 350 · 35 = 12250 (mod 1399). • Reduce 12250 modulo 1399: 1399·8 = 11192, 12250 − 11192 = 1058. Thus 160⁻¹ ≡ 1058 (mod 1399), i.e. 160·1058 ≡ 1 (mod 1399). Method 2 (extended Euclidean algorithm). 1399 = 8·160 + 119 160 = 1·119 + 41 119 = 2·41 + 37 41 = 1·37 + 4 37 = 9·4 + 1 Back-substituting gives 1 = 1058·160 − 121·1399, so 160·1058 ≡ 1 (mod 1399). Both methods yield the same residue 1058, and 0 ≤ 1058 < 1399 as required. 4. [Conclusion] The multiplicative inverse of 160 modulo 1399 is n = 1058.
